es in Somme and Aisne called Cambron. Alternatively, from a diminutive of <i>c(h)ambre</i> ‘room’ (see   Cambre  )."]},{"name":"Camron","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Cameron  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert Cameron III, Sixth Chief of Clan Cameron was born in 1209, in Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John Cameron - Fifth Chief of Clan Cameron, was 53 and his mother, Roberta, was 52. He had at least 1 son with Unknown Cameron. He died in 1250, in Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 41, and was buried in Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1209–1250":"1209–1250","–Female":"Surnud","1230–1320":"1230–1320","1156–1214":"1156–1214","1157–1214":"1157–1214","1214":"1214","1157":"1157","1156":"1156","1320":"1320","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1209":"1209","before 1209":"enne 1209","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Scotland","Lochiel, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Scotland","Lochiel, Invernesshire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire,